04493nam a22005175i 9780773566637DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19971997xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735666377 a10.1515/97807735666372doi  a(DE-B1597)655384  a(OCoLC)732600862  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHV1475.O6bM664 1997eb 7aMED0030502bisacsh04a362.6/09713/090341 aMontigny, Edgar-André, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFoisted upon the Government? :bState Responsibilities, Family Obligations, & Care of the Dependent Aged in Late 19th-Century Ont. /cEdgar-André Montigny. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's/Associated Medical Services Studies in the History of Medicine, Health, and Society ;v600tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPopulation Aging, Old-Age Dependency, and Public Policy in Historical Perspective -- tHome and Family: A Demographic Profile of the Aged in Nineteenth-Century Ontario: Brockville, 1851–1901 -- tDependency, Employment, and Need among Ontario’s Aged: Perception and Reality -- tFamilies, Neighbours, and Communities: Local Support Systems for the Aged Poor in Nineteenth-Century Ontario -- tGovernment Policy towards the Dependent Aged in Ontario: Institutions and the Ideal Family -- tInstitutions and the Impact of Public Policy on the Aged: The Elderly Patients of Rockwood Asylum, 1866–1906 -- tLong-Term-Care Reform and Family Obligations in Ontario in the 1990s -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile government officials in the 1890s claimed that forcing families to take responsibility for caring for the aged was in the interest of the elderly, Edgar-André Montigny reveals that government policy had more to with saving money than a desire to serve the aged. He provides a harsh critique of Ontario government policies toward the elderly and their families at the end of the nineteenth century and highlights similarities between what happened in the 1890s and current policy reforms in the area of long-term care. Montigny argues that government played a central role in determining how society viewed the elderly and family obligations to them. Using census data, municipal records, and institutional case files, he demonstrates that the government created and promoted an image of the aged population that bore little resemblance to reality and manipulated the concept of family obligations to justify policies to reduce social welfare costs. The effect of these policies, passed in the name of helping the elderly and their families, was almost universally negative. By dispelling the myths that continue to influence public policy concerning the aged, Montigny provides a useful warning of the negative consequences of policies that are enacted to cut costs rather than to serve the population they are supposed to help.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aMEDICAL / Allied Health Services / Occupational Therapy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356663740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773566637423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773566637/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles